Developing Models and Code to Test Bag Limit Policies in California State Fisheries

Tom Carruthers tom@bluematterscience.com

30 March, 2023

 

 

 

Disclaimer

The following work is preliminary and intended only as tool for eliciting feedback on data, modelling and other aspects of modelling bag limit regulations in MSE.

None of these results are final.

These analyses do not necessarily reflect the point of view of RLF, CDFW, or other funders and in no way anticipate future policy in this area.

Objective

Based on empirical data on recreational catch rate and discarding, for at least two species of california state fisheries, develop theoretical models that predict discard rates given alternative bag limit policies, and incorporate these into the open-source openMSE framework for testing management procedures.

Tasks

Task Status
A. Examine and analyze the CDFW recreational catch data for California halibut and one other case-study to calculate probability of catching or exceeding the bag limit at a given stock size. 0.5
B. Develop and describe the mathematical model used to calculate the impact of bag limits on the fishery dynamics, accounting for discard mortality and individual and boat bag limits and add to the openMSE framework as a management option that can be used in combination with other existing management options (e.g., TAC, TAE, etc.). 0.5
C. Apply the bag limit feature to California halibut and one other case-study (e.g., groundfish species) identified by CDFW collaborators. 0.4
D. Incorporate feedback from CDFW and other collaborators on technical documents and produce final project report. 0.0
E. Provide co-authorship support for drafting CDFW scientists-led manuscript describing the methods and results of the application to the case-studies. 0.0

 

Priorities

Priority To Do

1 Organize call to present work so far and get feedback on modelling
1 Reach out to r4SS developers to understand which version is needed to read the lastest assessments
1 Identify any missing regulations that need to be modelled (e.g. boat limits)
2 In consultation with CDFW, identify a suitable second species (recfin data, regulation data, assessment model available) and arrange transfer of assessment files
2 Convert halibut model to openMSE multi-OM (current demonstration is using an older generic openMSE OM to 2016 that does not include sex or fleet structure).
2 Undertake data analysis for second species to fit discarding model
